[[File:Berlin, Tiergarten, Grosser Tiergarten, Beethoven-Haydn-Mozart-Denkmal, Siemering, 1904.jpg|thumb|right|The memorial in 2013]]
The '''Beethoven-Haydn-Mozart Memorial''' ({{lang-de|Komponistendenkmal}}) is an outdoor 1904 memorial to the classical composers [[Ludwig van Beethoven]], [[Joseph Haydn]] and [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart]], designed by [[Rudolf Siemering|Rudolf]] and Wolfgang Siemering and located in [[Tiergarten (park)|Tiergarten]], [[Berlin]], Germany.<ref>{{cite news|title=Beethoven-Haydn-Mozart statue in Berlin vandalized with anti-Semitic graffiti|url=http://famagusta-gazette.com/beethovenhaydnmozart-statue-in-berlin-vandalized-with-antisemitic-graffi-p25513-69.htm|accessdate=29 June 2015|work=Famagusta Gazette|date=15 September 2014}}</ref> The monument was commissioned by [[Kaiser Wilhelm II]]. The monument suffered considerable damage during [[WWII]] and wasn't fully restored until 2007. After two years of restoration works, the Beethoven-Haydn-Mozart Denkmal was re-erected that year, providing the revitalized monument that can be seen today.<ref>{{cite news|title=Monument to classical composers at Tiergarten|url=https://www.tripadvisor.com/ShowUserReviews-g187323-d11841001-r451776760-Beethoven_Haydn_Mozart_Denkmal-Berlin.html|accessdate=3 March 2018|work=Famagusta Gazette|date=13 January 2017 }}</ref>

