{{Politics of Poland}}
'''Judiciary of Poland''' is a responsibility, as defined by the [[constitution of Poland]], of a four-tier [[court]] system: the [[Supreme Court of Poland]], the [[common court]]s, [[administrative court]]s (including the [[Supreme Administrative Court of Poland]]) and [[military court]]s. Therefore, [[tribunal]]s (such as the [[Constitutional Tribunal of the Republic of Poland|Constitutional Tribunal]] and [[State Tribunal of the Republic of Poland|State Tribunal]]) are, in a strict definition, not part of Polish judiciary, but in a broad definition, they are included in it.

The common courts, divided into [[appellate court]]s, [[district court]]s and [[regional court]]s, have the competency in criminal, civil, economic, labor and family law.

Court judges in Poland are nominated by the [[National Council of the Judiciary|Krajowa Rada Sądownictwa]] (National Council of the Judiciary) and are appointed for life by the [[president of Poland]].

[[Prosecution in Poland]] is formed by the [[Public Prosecutor General (Poland)|Public Prosecutor General]], the [[National Public Prosecutor's Office]], regional, district and appellate prosecutions, military prosecutors, and the prosecutors of the [[Institute of National Remembrance]].

== Reforms ==
The [[European Commission]] invokes the Article 7 of the [[Treaty on European Union|European Treaty]] against [[European Union|E.U.]] member [[Poland]], denouncing recent judiciary reforms putting it under the political control of the [[Law and Justice party|ruling majority]] and citing ''"serious risk [to] the [[rule of law|independence of the judiciary]] and the [[separation of powers]]"''. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/europe/article/2017/12/20/l-europe-declenche-une-procedure-sans-precedent-contre-le-gouvernement-polonais_5232406_3214.html |title=L’Europe déclenche une procédure sans précédent contre le gouvernement polonais |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=20 December 2017 |website=[[LeMonde.fr]] |access-date=26 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Poland Overhauls Judiciary, Escalating Clash With E.U. | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/20/world/europe/eu-poland-law.html | website = nytimes.com | date = 20 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Poland cries foul as EU triggers 'nuclear option' over judicial independence | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/dec/20/eu-process-poland-voting-rights | website = theguardian.com | date = 20 December 2017}}</ref>.

