{{Okinawan name|Kikuin}}
{{unref|date=June 2017}}
{{nihongo|'''Kikuin Sōi'''|菊隠 宗意|extra=? &ndash; 1620}} was a [[Rinzai school|Rinzai]] [[Japanese Zen|Zen]] [[Buddhist monk]] of the [[Ryukyu Kingdom]].

Kikuin was ordained as a [[Bhikkhu]] (full monk) at the [[Enkaku-ji (Okinawa)|Enkaku-ji]] temple ({{lang|ja|円覚寺}}) in Shuri. Later, he travelled to Japan to study Zen for over ten years. After he returned to Ryukyu, he was appointed [[Abbot (Buddhism)|abbot]] of [[Tennō-ji (Okinawa)|Tennō-ji]] temple ({{lang|ja|天王寺}}). Kikuin was fluent in [[Japanese language|Japanese]]; he was friends of [[Shimazu Yoshihisa]], [[Shimazu Yoshihiro]] and [[Shimazu Tadatsune|Shimazu Iehisa]]. He led missions to [[Satsuma Domain]] multiple times.

In the spring of 1609, [[invasion of Ryukyu|Satsuma invaded Ryukyu]] and captured the strategically important [[Nakijin Castle]]. Kikuin went there to request a peace negotiation together with a Japanese tea master named [[Kian (tea master)|Kian]], but they were arrested by Satsuma troops. After the war, he was taken to [[Kagoshima Castle]] together with King [[Shō Nei]] and a number of high officials by Satsuma troops. After ''[[sessei]]'' [[Gushichan Chōsei]] died at [[Sunpu Castle]], he served as acting ''sessei''.


