{{Expand Czech|topic=culture|date=August 2010|Pražský dobrodruh}}
'''''Pražský dobrodruh, podivuhodná historie Hanuše Adama Löwenmachta''''' (''Prague Adventurer: the marvelous story of Hans Adam Löwenmacht''), originally published in German as ''Hans Adam Löwenmacht, phantastischer Roman aus der Barockzeit'', is an adventure novel, described as a "[[Baroque]] novel", by [[Rudolf Slawitschek]], a [[Czechoslovakia|Czech]] writer who wrote in [[German language|German]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.databazeknih.cz/knihy/prazsky-dobrodruh-podivuhodna-historie-h-a-lowenmachta-199610|title=Pražský dobrodruh - Podivuhodná historie H.A.Löwenmachta - Rudolf Slawitschek |work= Databáze knih|access-date=4 August 2018}}</ref> It is the author's best-known work and won the [[Prague City Prize]] in 1940.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kohoutikriz.org/data/w_slawi.php|title=Rudolf Slawitschek: životopis jednoho spisovatele z Čech |first1=Robert N. |last=Bloch|work=Kohoutí kříž|editor-last1=Mareš|editor-first1=Jan|editor-last2=Kareš|editor-first2=Ivo|language=cs|access-date=2018-08-04}}
</ref> The adventure novel takes place in the historical city of Prague.

The first German edition was published by [[Rudolf M. Rohrer Verlag]] in 1939 
A [[Czech language|Czech-language]] version was first published in 1942 by [[Josef R. Vilímek]] publishing house, translated by [[S. Möcklová]]. The cover illustration of the novel was created by [[Zdeněk Guth]].

The second Czech edition of the novel in 1943 was affected by the linguistic regulations of the occupation administration. The most significant manifestation was the ban on the translation of German city names into Czech.

